    <question>
        <prompt>Calvin Coolidge's statement "the business of America is business" reflected:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Support for labor unions</option>
            <option letter="b">Pro-business, laissez-faire philosophy</option>
            <option letter="c">Government regulation</option>
            <option letter="d">Progressive reform agenda</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Coolidge's famous statement encapsulated his pro-business, laissez-faire philosophy. His administration emphasized minimal government intervention in the economy, reduced regulations, lowered taxes on businesses and wealthy individuals, and generally supported private enterprise. This approach characterized the conservative, business-friendly political climate of the "Roaring Twenties."</explanation>
    </question>
